'''Okada Shrine''' (おかだじんじゃ) is a shrine in {{jalink|Matsumoto|Q213324}}, {{jalink|Nagano Prefecture|Q127877}}. It is a {{jalink|Shikinaisha}} recorded in the ''{{jalink|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932}}'', and under the old shrine-ranking system its rank was district shrine.

=== Overview ===
The enshrined deity is {{jalink|Ukemochi no Kami|Q2280323}}. Shrine tradition says it was founded in 654 (Hakuchi 5), and it is considered a shrine that venerates a water spirit deity of the five grains and rich harvest. The approach extends about 600 meters: the first torii stands at the entrance of Okada-juku on the former {{jalink|Hokkoku Saigai-dō|Q11401310}}, followed by the second torii, worship hall, and main hall. On both sides of the main hall are 15 massha including Hachiman Shrine. In the early Meiji period, the precinct measured 46 ken east-west and 21 ken north-south. As an inner shrine, Mizuguchi-sha is enshrined upstream on the {{jalink|Metoba River|Q11446607}}.

=== References ===
* ''Nagano Prefecture Town and Village Records'' (1876)
* ''Shinshū no Bunka Series: Temples and Shrines'' (1981), {{jalink|Shinano Mainichi Shimbun|Q11386181|Shinano Mainichi Shimbun Co.}}
* Edited by {{jalink|Tanigawa Ken'ichi|Q2392596}}: ''Gods of Japan - Shrines and Sacred Places - 9 Mino/Hida/Shinano'' (2000), {{jalink|Hakusuisha|Q4346470}}
=== Related articles ===
* {{jalink|Matsumoto#famous places and historic sites|Q213324|Famous places and historic sites of Matsumoto}}
* {{jalink|History of Matsumoto|Q11531022}}
